    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Broad, flattened isopod with abdominal segments fused and joined to telson to form a ‘pleotelson’. Able to roll into a ball when disturbed. Pleotelson large with broad uropods. The most distinctive feature is the very large backward-sloping dorsal spike emerging from the centre of the last thoracic segment in males. The pleotelson of males also has a distinctive wide keyhole-shaped notch at its tip. Females lack the dorsal spike and keyhole on the pleotelson, which instead has two small humps.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_541",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Up to 6 mm, excluding antennae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_542",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to region.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Northern Namibia to about East London.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_543",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Poorly known, but fairly common on rocky shores, particularly under boulders and in kelp holdfasts. The role of the rather awkward-looking dorsal spike is unknown, but it might make males more difficult for predators to swallow.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_544",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Assumed to feed on algae.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_545",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>As in all isopods the eggs are retained in a marsupial chamber between the walking legs of females, where they develop into fully-formed young prior to release.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_546",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>One of only two species in this endemic genus. The male of the other species,<i> P. stimpsoni, </i>has a very short double-tipped horn on the last thoracic segment, a much smaller ‘keyhole’ and a ring of small tubercles on the pleotelson. Females also have the short horn, but no keyhole. &nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_547",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2016). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fourth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 90).<br><br>Kensley, B (1978). Guide to the Marine Isopods of Southern Africa. <i>Trustees of the South African Museum</i>, Cape Town. 173 pp. (p. 110).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_548",
